  "chunk_index": 50,
  "summary": "In a church, Muto explains to the group that Mistuho’s fanatical ideals were designed to transform Kaji into a symbolic \"god.\" According to Muto, Kaji had to undergo a \"purification\" through death to achieve eternal brilliance and live forever in Mistuho's heart, framing the murders as a holy war committed by the \"mist-drawn\" to fulfill their faith. Muto then reveals that Fujiko is at the \"Hell Gate,\" comparing her situation to the ending of the \"Japanese Thrush Mystery,\" suggesting she chose suicide to complete a narrative epic and escape divine laws.\n\nThe group enters \"Hell's Gate\" and finds a guillotine in the center of the room. Fujiko lies on the device, her hand gripping the knife used in ten murders. As a prophecy etched beneath the guillotine is fulfilled, her severed head radiates a cold light. Despite the violence, Fujiko appears serene, having found redemption and becoming a \"god.\"\n\nFollowing the conclusion of the case, the narrator feels a sense of emptiness and returns to the central hall. He discovers a hidden passage behind a tilted portrait of Ochiba. Descending a staircase and passing through an iron door, he enters a basement corridor that resembles a prison. He eventually reaches a stone room containing the coffin of the deceased Domo. While sitting on the coffin and smoking, the narrator realizes a murderer is hiding behind the coffin in the corner. He addresses the silent figure, acknowledging that they performed a great job and remained unsuspected.",
